{"title_page": "Kingdom of Israel (united monarchy)", "text_new": "{{about||the modern country|State of Israel|the two split kingdoms|Kingdom of Israel (Samaria)|and|Kingdom of Judah}}\n{{Infobox Former Country\n|native_name = \ud802\udd09\ud802\udd14\ud802\udd13\ud802\udd00\ud802\udd0b<ref>\n* {{cite book |last=Rollston |first=Chris A. |author-link=Christopher Rollston |title=Writing and Literacy in the World of Ancient Israel: Epigraphic Evidence from the Iron Age |year=2010 |publisher=Society of Biblical Literature |url=http://books.google.co.kr/books?id=kx9Uke_IfloC&pg=PA52 |pages=52\u201354 |isbn=978-1589831070 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Compston |first=Herbert F. B. |title=The Inscription on the Stele of M\u00e9\u0161a\u02bf |year=1919 |url=http://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Inscription_on_the_Stele_of_M%C3%A9%C5%A1a%CA%BF }}</ref>\n|conventional_long_name = Kingdom of Israel\n|common_name      = Kingdom of Israel\n|era              = [[Iron Age]]\n|government_type  = [[Hereditary monarchy|Hereditary]], [[Theocracy|theocratic]], and [[Absolute monarchy|absolute]] monarchy\n|common_languages = Hebrew, Aramaic\n|religion         = [[Yahwism]]<br>[[Polytheism]]<br>([[Canaanite Religion|Canaanite]] \u2022<br> [[Ancient Mesopotamian religion|Mesopotamian]] \u2022<br> [[Folk religion]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Ezekiel+8&version=NIV|title=Bible Gateway passage: Ezekiel 8 - New International Version|website=Bible Gateway}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://biblehub.com/1_kings/11-5.htm|title=1 Kings 11:5 Solomon followed Ashtoreth the goddess of the Sidonians and Molech the abomination of the Ammonites|website=biblehub.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://biblehub.com/2_kings/23-13.htm|title=2 Kings 23:13 The king also desecrated the high places east of Jerusalem, to the south of the Mount of Corruption, which King Solomon of Israel had built for Ashtoreth the abomination of the Sidonians, for Chemosh the abomination of the Moabites, and for Molech the abomination of the Ammonites|website=biblehub.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://biblehub.com/jeremiah/11-13.htm|title=Jeremiah 11:13 Your gods are indeed as numerous as your cities, O Judah, and the altars of shame you have set up--the altars to burn incense to Baal--are as many as the streets of Jerusalem|website=biblehub.com}}</ref><ref name=Finkelstein2001/>{{rp|240\u2013243}}\n|p1               = Tribes of Israel\n|flag_p1          = Menorah.svg\n|image_p1         = 12 Tribes of Israel Map.svg\n|image_map        = Kingdom of Israel 1020 map.svg\n|s1               = Kingdom of Israel (Samaria)\n|flag_s1          = Menorah.svg\n|s2               = Kingdom of Judah\n|flag_s2          = Menorah.svg\n|event_start      = [[Saul|Saul's ascension]]\n|year_start       = c. 1047 BCE\n|event_end        = [[Jeroboam's Revolt]]\n|year_end         = 930 BCE\n|capital          = [[Gibeah]] <small>(1030\u20131010 BCE)</small><br /> [[Mahanaim]] <small>(1010\u20131008)</small><br /> [[Hebron]] <small>(1008\u20131003)</small><br /> [[Jerusalem]] <small>(1003\u2013930)</small>\n|leader1          = [[Saul]]\n|leader2          = [[Ish-boseth|Ishbaal]]\n|leader3          = [[David]]\n|leader4          = [[Solomon]]\n|leader5          = [[Rehoboam]]\n|year_leader1     = 1047\u20131010 BCE\n|year_leader2     = 1010\u20131008\n|year_leader3     = 1008\u2013970\n|year_leader4     = 970\u2013931\n|year_leader5     = 931\u2013930\n|title_leader     = [[Kings of Israel and Judah|King]]\n|today            = \n{{flag|Egypt}}<br>{{flag|Israel}}<br>{{flag|Jordan}}<br>{{flag|Lebanon}}<br>{{flag|Palestine}}<br>{{flag|Syria}}\n}}\n\nThe '''United Monarchy''' ({{Lang-he-n|\u05d4\u05de\u05de\u05dc\u05db\u05d4 \u05d4\u05de\u05d0\u05d5\u05d7\u05d3\u05ea}}) is the name given to the [[Israelites|Israelite]]{{refn|group=note|name=israelite|This article uses the term \"Israelite\" as defined by ''The Encyclopedia of the Jewish Religion'': <blockquote>The name . . . signifies the people composed of &#91;[[Jacob]]'s&#93; descendants (the \"[[children of Israel]]\"), being applied (a) to the [[Twelve Tribes of Israel|whole people]] (including [[Tribe of Judah|Judah]]) . . . [but] (b) with the division of the kingdom after the death of [[Solomon]], to the [[Northern Kingdom]] only.\"<ref name=\"werblowskiwigoder1966\">{{cite book|chapter=Israelite|title=The Encyclopedia of the Jewish Religion|editor-last1=Werblowsky|editor-first1=R.J. Zwi|editor-link1=R.J. Zwi Werblowsky|editor-last2=Wigoder|editor-first2=Geoffrey|publisher=Holt, Rinehart and Winston|date=1966|pages=206\u2013207}}</ref></blockquote> }} kingdom of Israel and Judah,<ref name=\"cundall1972\">{{cite journal|author-last=Cundall|author-first=Arthur E. |title=The United Monarchy: fact or fiction?|journal= Vox Evangelica |volume=8 |year=1973|pages= 33\u201339|url=http://www.biblicalstudies.org.uk/pdf/vox/vol08/monarchy_cundall.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"harvey1996\">{{cite book|author-last=Harvey|author-first=Graham|date=1996|title=The True Israel: Uses of the Names Jew, Hebrew, and Israel in Ancient Jewish and Early Christian Literature|publisher=Brill Academic Publishers, Inc.|location=Boston|page=164|isbn=978-0-391-04119-6|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Dy5D90UapWsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref><ref name=\"devaux1997\">{{cite book|last=de Vaux, O.P.|first=Roland|author-link=Roland de Vaux|translator-last=McHugh|translator-first=John|date=1997|title=Ancient Israel: Its Life and Institutions|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|location=Grand Rapids, Michigan|isbn=978-0-8028-4278-7|url=https://books.google.com/?id=A42yVk8kj8kC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> during the reigns of [[Saul]], [[David]] and [[Solomon]], as depicted in the [[Hebrew Bible]]. This is traditionally dated between 1050 BCE and 930 BCE. On the succession of Solomon's son, [[Rehoboam]], around 930 BCE, the biblical account reports that the country split into two kingdoms: the [[Kingdom of Israel (Samaria)|Kingdom of Israel]] (including the cities of [[Shechem]] and [[Samaria (ancient city)|Samaria]]) in the north and the [[Kingdom of Judah]] (containing Jerusalem) in the south.\n\nIn contemporary scholarship the united monarchy is generally held to be a literary construction and not a historical reality, pointing to the lack of archaeological evidence. It is generally accepted that a \"[[Davidic line|House of David]]\" existed, but many believe that David could have only been the monarch or [[chieftain]] of Judah, which was likely small, and that the northern kingdom was a separate development. There are some dissenters to this view.<ref name=\"lipschits\">{{cite book|last1=Lipschits|first1=Oded|editor1-last=Berlin|editor1-first=Adele|editor2-last=Brettler|editor2-first=Marc Zvi|title=The Jewish Study Bible|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-997846-5|year=2014|edition=2nd|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yErYBAAAQBAJ&dq|language=en|chapter=The history of Israel in the biblical period}}</ref><ref name=\"Finkelstein2001\">{{cite book|last1=Finkelstein|first1=Israel|author-link1=Israel Finkelstein|last2=Silberman|first2=Neil Asher|author-link2=Neil Asher Silberman|title=The Bible Unearthed: Archaeology's New Vision of Ancient Israel and the Origin of its Stories|date=2001|publisher=Simon & Schuster|location=New York|isbn=978-0-684-86912-4|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lu6ywyJr0CMC&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Bible+Unearthed:+Archaeology%27s+New+Vision+of+Ancient+Israel+and+the+Origin+of+its+Stories#v=onepage&q=The%20Bible%20Unearthed%3A%20Archaeology's%20New%20Vision%20of%20Ancient%20Israel%20and%20the%20Origin%20of%20its%20Stories&f=false}}</ref><ref name=Kuhrtp438>{{cite book|last=Kuhrt|first=Am\u00e9lie|author-link=Am\u00e9lie Kuhrt|title=The Ancient Near East, c. 3000-330 BC, Band 1|year=1995|publisher=Routledge|location=New York|isbn=978-0-41516-762-8|page=438|url=https://books.google.com/?id=V_sfMzRPTgoC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Kuhrt,+Amiele+(1995).+The+Ancient+Near+East.#v=onepage&q=Kuhrt%2C%20Amiele%20(1995).%20The%20Ancient%20Near%20East.&f=false}}</ref><ref name=\"bibleinterp.com\">{{cite web|last1=Wright|first1=Jacob L.|author-link=Jacob L. Wright|title=David, King of Judah (not Israel)|url=http://www.bibleinterp.com/articles/2014/07/wri388001.shtml|website=The Bible and Interpretation|date=July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n{{Main|Books of Samuel|History of Ancient Israel and Judah}}\nAccording to standard [[Source criticism (biblical studies)|source criticism]], a number of distinct source texts were spliced together to produce the current Books of Samuel.<ref name=\"bibleinterp.com\"/> The most prominent in the early parts of the first book are the pro-monarchical source and the anti-monarchical source. In identifying these two sources, two separate accounts can be reconstructed. The anti-monarchical source describes [[Samuel (Bible)|Samuel]] as having thoroughly routed the [[Philistines]], yet begrudgingly accepting the people's demand for a ruler, subsequently appointing Saul by [[cleromancy]].{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\nThe pro-monarchical source describes the divinely appointed birth of [[Saul]] (a single word being changed by a later editor so that it referred to Samuel instead), and his leading of an army to victory over the [[Ammon (nation)|Ammonites]], resulted in the clamouring of the people for him to lead them against the Philistines, whereupon he is appointed king.<ref name=\"jones2001\">{{Cite book|last=Jones|first=Gwilym H.|chapter=1 and 2 Samuel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wCRYl9Ikk6EC&pg=PA196|editor-last1=Barton|editor-first1=John|editor-link1=John Barton (theologian)|editor-last2=Muddiman|editor-first2=John|editor-link2=John Muddiman|title=The Oxford Bible Commentary|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2001|pages= 197\u2013199|isbn=978-0-19875-500-5}}</ref>\n\n[[Textual critic]]s also point to disparities in the account of David's rise to power as indicative of separate threads being merged later to create a [[Golden Age]] of a united monarchy. David is thought by scholars to have been a ruler in Judah, while Israel, comparatively immense and highly developed, continued unfettered. [[Modern archaeology]] also supports this view.<ref name=Finkelstein2001/>\n\nMost scholars believe the Books of Samuel exhibit too many [[anachronism]]s to have been a contemporary account. For example, there is mention of later [[armor]] (1 Samuel 17:4\u20137, 38\u201339; 25:13), use of [[camel]]s (1 Samuel 30:17), [[cavalry]] (as distinct from [[chariotry]]) (1 Samuel 13:5, 2 Samuel 1:6), and iron picks and axes (as though they were common) (2 Samuel 12:31). The historicity of the conquest described in the Book of Samuel is not attested, and many scholars regard this conquest as legendary in origin, particularly given the lack of evidence for the battles described involving the destruction of the Canaanite peoples. Most scholars believe that Samuel was compiled in the 8th century BCE (rather than the 10th century when most of the events described take place) based on both historical and legendary sources, primarily serving to fill the gap in Israelite history after the events described in [[Deuteronomy]]. This gap in the historical record is characteristic of the [[Late Bronze Age collapse]];<ref name=\"AruzSeymour2016\">{{cite book|editor-first1=Joan|editor-last1=Aruz|editor-first2=Michael|editor-last2=Seymour|first=Ann E.|last=Killebrew|title=Assyria to Iberia: Art and Culture in the Iron Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WBrfDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA38|date=30 December 2016|publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art|isbn=978-1-58839-606-8|pages=30\u201338}}</ref> cultural memories of times before the disaster often became embellished as stories of a \"lost golden age\", as in the Trojan [[Epic Cycle]].<ref name=\"Kalimi2018\">Cf. {{cite book|first=Isaac|last=Kalimi|title=Writing and Rewriting the Story of Solomon in Ancient Israel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L9Z7DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA47|date=29 November 2018|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-108-58837-9|pages=47\u201348}}</ref>\n\n==Archaeological record==\n\nAccording to [[Israel Finkelstein]] and [[Neil Asher Silberman|Neil Silberman]], authors of ''[[The Bible Unearthed]]'', ideas of a united monarchy are not accurate history but rather \"creative expressions of a powerful religious reform movement,\" possibly \"based on certain historical kernels.\"<ref name=Finkelstein2001/> Finkelstein and Silberman do accept that David and Solomon were real kings of Judah about the 10th century BCE, but they cite the fact that the earliest independent reference to the Kingdom of Israel dates to about 890 BCE, while that for the kingdom of Judah dates to about 750 BCE.<ref name=\"finkelsteinsilberman2007\">{{cite book |last1=Finkelstein |first1=Israel |last2=Silberman |first2=Neil Asher |title=David and Solomon: In Search of the Bible's Sacred Kings and the Roots of the Western Tradition |date=2007 |publisher=Simon and Schuster |location=New York |isbn=978-1-416-55688-6 |page=20 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/David_and_Solomon.html?id=uH7Kg9yEc7AC}}</ref> This is supported by Jonathan Tubb, who argues that the story of the united monarchy was fabricated as a Golden Age tale during the [[Babylonian captivity|Exile]]. He accepts the historicity of David and Solomon but cautions that \"[t]hey must be seen . . . as local [[folk hero]]es and not as rulers of international status.\"<ref name=Tubbp115>{{cite book|last=Tubb|first=Jonathan|title=Canaanites|year=2006|publisher=The British Museum Press|location=London|isbn=978-0-7141-2766-8|page=115}}</ref> [[Oded Lipschits]] wrote in the ''Jewish Study Bible'' that \"the premonarchic period long ago became a literary description of the mythological roots, the early beginnings of the nation and the way to describe the right of Israel on its land. The archeological evidence also does not support the existence of a united monarchy under David and Solomon as described in the Bible, so the rubric of \"united monarchy\" is best abandoned, although it remains useful for discussing how the Bible views the Israelite past\".<ref name=\"lipschits\"/>\n\nOn the other hand, while [[Am\u00e9lie Kuhrt]] does acknowledge that \"there are no royal inscriptions from the time of the united monarchy (indeed very little written material altogether), and not a single contemporary reference to either David or Solomon,\" she concludes that \"[a]gainst this must be set the evidence for substantial development and growth at several sites, which is plausibly related to the tenth century.\"<ref name=Kuhrtp438 /> [[Kenneth Kitchen]] reaches a similar conclusion, arguing that \"the physical archaeology of tenth-century [[Canaan]] is consistent with the former existence of a unified state on its terrain.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Kitchen|first=Kenneth|title=On the Reliability of the Old Testament|year=2003|publisher=William B. Eerdmans Publishing Company|location=Grand Rapids, Michigan|isbn=978-0-80280-396-2|page=158|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Kw6U05qBiXcC&lpg=PA158&dq=%22the%20physical%20archaeology%20of%20tenth-century%20Canaan%20is%20consistent%20with%20the%20former%20existence%20of%20a%20unified%20state%20on%20its%20terrain%22&pg=PA158#v=onepage&q=%22the%20physical%20archaeology%20of%20tenth-century%20Canaan%20is%20consistent%20with%20the%20former%20existence%20of%20a%20unified%20state%20on%20its%20terrain%22&f=false}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Qeiyafa city wall1.jpg|right|thumb|Aerial view of [[Khirbet Qeiyafa]].]]\nExcavations at [[Khirbet Qeiyafa]], an [[Iron Age]] site located in Judah, found an urbanized settlement [[radiocarbon dated]] well before scholars such as Finklestein suggest [[urbanization]] began in Judah, supporting existence of a Judahite kingdom. The [[Israel Antiquities Authority]] stated: \"The excavations at Khirbat Qeiyafa clearly reveal an urban society that existed in Judah already in the late eleventh century BCE. It can no longer be argued that the Kingdom of Judah developed only in the late eighth century BCE or at some other later date.\"<ref name=\"garfinkel2012\">{{cite web |last1=Garfinkel |first1=Yossi |last2=Ganor |first2=Sa'ar |last3=Hasel |first3=Michael |title=Journal 124: Khirbat Qeiyafa preliminary report |url=http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=1989 |website=Hadashot Arkheologiyot: Excavations and Surveys in Israel |publisher=Israel Antiquities Authority |accessdate=12 June 2018 |ref=garfinkel2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623021750/http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=1989 |archivedate=1 January 2018 |date=19 April 2012}}</ref> The techniques and interpretations used to reach some conclusions related to Khirbet Qeiyafa have been criticized by some scholars, among them Finkelstein and Alexander Fantalkin of [[Tel Aviv University]].<ref name=\"finkelsteinfantalkin2012\">{{cite journal |last1=Finkelstein |first1=Israel |last2=Fantalkin |first2=Alexander |title=Khirbet Qeiyafa: an unsensational archaeological and historical interpretation |journal=Tel Aviv |date=May 2012 |volume=39 |pages=38\u201363 |doi=10.1179/033443512x13226621280507 |url=http://archaeology.tau.ac.il/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/Qeiyafa_Unsensational_Interpretation.pdf |accessdate=12 June 2018 |ref=finkelsteinfantalkin2012}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, Israeli archaeologists discovered massive [[fortification]]s in the ruins of the ancient city of [[Gath (city)|Gath]], supposed birthplace of [[Goliath]]. The size of the fortifications show Gath to have been a very large city in the 10th century BCE, perhaps the largest in Canaan at the time. The professor leading the dig, [[Aren Maeir]], estimated that Gath was as much as four times the size of contemporary Jerusalem, casting doubt that David's kingdom could have been as powerful as described in the Bible.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.haaretz.com/beta/.premium-1.669425|title=Philistine city of Gath a lot more powerful than thought, archaeologists suggest|last1=Hasson|first1=Nir |work=Haaretz|publisher=Haaretz Daily Newspaper Ltd.|date=4 August 2015|accessdate=12 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Finkelstein claimed that mounting evidence from archaeological digs has led him to believe that a united monarchy of sorts did exist, but that it was under [[Jeroboam II]], some two centuries after the reigns of David and Solomon. Finkelstein claimed that the Biblical narrative was likely invented under the reign of King [[Josiah]] to justify expansion and that the historical united monarchy was the inspiration.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/archaeology/.premium.MAGAZINE-meet-the-real-king-david-the-one-the-bible-didn-t-want-you-to-know-about-1.7062754|title=Meet the Real King David, the One the Bible Didn\u2019t Want You to Know About|last=David|first=Ariel|date=2019-03-27|work=Haaretz|access-date=2019-04-24|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Biblical narrative==\n===Origin===\n{{History of Israel}}\nAccording to the [[Book of Judges]], before the rise of the united monarchy the [[Israelite]] tribes lived as a [[Confederated Tribes of Israel|confederation]] under ''[[ad hoc]]'' [[charisma]]tic leaders called [[Biblical judges|judges]]. [[Abimelech (Judges)|Abimelech]] the first judge to be declared king by the men of [[Shechem]] and the house of Millo (Bet Millo), reigned over Israel for three years before he was killed during the Battle of [[Tubas|Thebez]].\n\nAccording to the biblical account, the united monarchy was formed when there was a large popular expression in favour of introducing a king to rule over the decentralised Israelite confederacy. Increasing pressure from the [[Philistines]] and other neighboring peoples is said by the Bible to have forced the Israelites to unite as state following the [[anointing]] of Saul by Samuel. The Bible treats the notion of kingship as having been [[anathema]], it being viewed as the placing of one man in a position of reverence and power that ought to be reserved for [[God]].<ref>{{cite web |title=1 Samuel 8.6 |url=https://www.sefaria.org/I_Samuel.8.7?lang=en |website=Sefaria |accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Civil war===\nDavid and Saul become bitter enemies, at least from Saul's point of view, although sources describe [[Jonathan (1 Samuel)|Jonathan]], Saul's son, and [[Michal]], Saul's daughter and David's first wife, as assisting David to escape Saul, ultimately leading to a brief reconciliation before Saul's death.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\nAccording to the [[Second Book of Samuel]], Saul's disobedience prompts God to curtail his reign and hand his kingdom over to another dynasty. Saul dies in battle against the Philistines{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} after a reign of just two years.<ref>Lemaire, Andre. [http://www.myjewishlearning.com/history/Ancient_and_Medieval_History/2500_BCE-539_BCE/Social_History/Sauls_United_Kingdom.shtml?p=2 \"King Saul.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527220959/http://www.myjewishlearning.com/history/Ancient_and_Medieval_History/2500_BCE-539_BCE/Social_History/Sauls_United_Kingdom.shtml?p=2 |date=2014-05-27 }} ''My Jewish Learning''.  27 May 2014.</ref> His heir, [[Ish-bosheth|Ishbaal]], rules for only two years before being [[assassination|assassinated]]. David, heretofore king of Judah only, ends the conspiracy and is appointed king of Israel in Ishbaal's place. Some textual critics and biblical scholars suggest that David was actually responsible for the assassination and that David's innocence was a later invention to legitimize his actions.<ref>{{cite book|author=Stanley Jerome Isser|title=The Sword of Goliath: David in Heroic Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OHT6Y-6RCewC&pg=PA152|date=January 2003|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-12737-1|pages=152\u2013}}</ref>\n\nIsrael [[insurrection|rebels]] against David and appoints David's son [[Absalom]] king, forcing David into [[exile]] east of the [[Jordan River|Jordan]].{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} David eventually launches a successful counterattack that results in the loss of Absalom. Having retaken Judah and asserted control over Israel, David returns west of the Jordan. Throughout the remainder of his reign, he continues to suppress rebellions that arise among the people of Israel.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\nThis section of the biblical text, and the bulk of the remainder of the Books of Samuel, is thought by textual critics to belong to a single large source known as the [[Court History of David]]. Although reflecting the [[polemic|political bias]] of the kingdom of Judah following the [[Kingdom of Israel (Samaria)#Destruction of the kingdom|destruction of Israel]], the source remains somewhat more neutral than the pro- and antimonarchical sources comprising earlier parts of the text. Israel and Judah are portrayed in this source as quite distinct kingdoms.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n===Golden Age===\nPrior to the ascension of Saul, the city of [[Shiloh (Biblical)|Shiloh]] is seen as the [[national capital]], at least in the religious sense, a claim that from an archaeological standpoint is considered plausible. Throughout the monarchy of Saul, the capital is located in [[Gibeah]]. After Saul's death, Ishbaal rules over the kingdom of Israel from [[Mahanaim]], while David establishes the capital of the kingdom of Judah in [[Hebron]].{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n \nFollowing the [[civil war]] with Saul, David forges a strong and unified Israelite monarchy, reigning c. 1000 to 961 BCE<ref name=\"Judges Chronology\">{{cite book|last=Edited by Robert G. Boling|title=Judges (The Anchor Yale Bible Commentaries)|year=1975|publisher=Doubleday|location=Garden City, New York|isbn=978-0300139457|page=XXI}}</ref> and establishing [[Jerusalem]] as his national capital in 1006 BCE.<ref name=\"aice2018\">{{cite web |title=The Jewish temples: Jerusalem in the First Temple Period (1006\u2013586 BCE) |url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jerusalem-in-the-first-temple-period |website=Jewish Virtual Library |publisher=American-Israeli Cooperative Enterprise |accessdate=14 June 2018 |ref=aice2018}}</ref> Some modern archaeologists, however, believe that the two distinct cultures and geographic entities of Judah and Israel continued uninterrupted, and that if a political union between them did exist, it possibly had no practical effect on their relationship.<ref name=Finkelstein2001/>\n\nIn the biblical account, David embarks on successful military campaigns against the enemies of Judah and Israel, defeating such regional entities as the [[Philistines]] to secure his borders. Israel grows from kingdom to empire, its sphere of influence\u2014militarily and politically\u2014expanding to control the weaker [[client state]]s of [[Philistia]], [[Moab]], [[Edom]] and [[Ammon]], with Aramaean [[city-state]]s [[Zobah|Aram-Zobah]] and [[Aram-Damascus]] becoming [[vassal state]]s.<ref>{{Bibleverse|2 Sam|8:1-14|NRSV}}</ref> The imperial border is described as stretching from the [[Mediterranean Sea]] to the [[Arabian Desert]], from the [[Red Sea]] to the [[Euphrates River]]. Some modern archaeologists believe that the area under the control of Judah and Israel, excluding the [[Phoenicia]]n territories on the shore of the [[Mediterranean]], did not exceed 34,000 square kilometres (13,000 sq mi), of which the kingdom of Israel encompassed about {{convert|24000|km2}}.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}}\n\nDavid is succeeded by his son [[Solomon]], who obtains the throne in a somewhat disreputable manner from rival claimant [[Adonijah]], his elder brother.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} The reign of Solomon (c. 961 to 922 BCE)<ref name=\"Judges Chronology\" /> proves to be a period of unprecedented peace, prosperity, and cultural development. Solomon embarks on an aggressive campaign of public building, erecting the [[Solomon's Temple|First Temple]] in Jerusalem with assistance from the [[King Hiram I|King of Tyre]], with whom he has maintained the strong alliance forged by his father.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} Like the [[David's Palace|palace of David]], Solomon's temple is designed and built with the assistance of Tyrian architects, master craftsmen, skilled labourers, money, jewels, cedar, and other goods obtained in exchange for land ceded to [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]].{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\nSolomon goes on to rebuild numerous major cities, including [[Tel Megiddo|Megiddo]], [[Tel Hazor|Hazor]], and [[Gezer]]. Some scholars have attributed aspects of archaeological remains excavated from this sites, including six-chambered gates and [[ashlar]] palaces, to this building programme. However, excavation teams at Megiddo later established that these structures are from different time periods. [[Yigael Yadin]] subsequently concluded that the stables once believed to have served Solomon's vast collection of horses were actually built by [[King Ahab]] in the 9th century BCE.<ref name=\"finkelsteinmaza2007\">{{cite book|last1=Finkelstein|first1=Israel|last2=Maza|first2=Amihay|date=2007|title=The Quest for the Historical Israel|location=Atlanta|publisher=Society of Biblical Literature|isbn=978-1-58983-277-0|page=102|url=https://books.google.com/?id=jpbngoKHg8gC&q=102#v=snippet&q=102&f=false}}</ref>\n\n===End===\n{{Main|Jeroboam's Revolt|Kingdom of Israel (Samaria)|Kingdom of Judah}}\n[[File:Kingdoms of Israel and Judah map 830.svg|thumb|Map showing the Kingdoms of Israel (blue) and Judah (orange), ancient Southern Levant borders and ancient cities such as Urmomium and Jerash. The map shows the region in the 9th century BCE.]]\nFollowing Solomon's death in c. 926 BCE, tensions between the northern part of Israel containing the ten northern tribes, and the southern section dominated by Jerusalem and the southern tribes reached boiling point. When Solomon's successor [[Rehoboam]] dealt tactlessly with economic complaints of the northern tribes, in about 930 BCE (there are differences of opinion as to the actual year) the United Kingdom of Israel and Judah split into two kingdoms: the northern [[Kingdom of Israel (Samaria)|Kingdom of Israel]], which included the cities of [[Shechem]] and [[Samaria]], and the southern [[Kingdom of Judah]], which contained Jerusalem, with most of the non-Israelite provinces achieving independence.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nThe Kingdom of Israel (or Northern Kingdom, or Samaria) existed as an independent state until 722 BCE when it was conquered by the [[Assyrian Empire]], while the Kingdom of Judah (or Southern Kingdom) existed as an independent state until 586 BCE when it was conquered by the [[Neo-Babylonian Empire]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==Biblical chronology==\n{{Further|Kings of Israel and Judah}}\nMany alternative chronologies have been suggested, and there is no ultimate consensus between the different factions and scholarly disciplines concerned with this period, as to when it is depicted as having begun or when it ended.<ref>{{cite book|last=Shanks|first=Hershel|title=Ancient Israel (3rd Edition)|year=2010|publisher=Pearson|isbn=978-0205096435}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Friedman|first=Richard|title=Who Wrote The Bible|year=1987|publisher=HarperOne|isbn=978-0060630355|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/whowrotebible000frie}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Bloom|first=Harold|title=The Book of J|year=2004|publisher=Grove Press|isbn=978-0802141910}}</ref>\n\nMost bibical scholars follow either of the older chronologies established by [[William F. Albright]] or [[Edwin R. Thiele]], or the newer chronology of [[Gershon Galil]], all of which are shown below. All dates are BCE. Thiele's chronology generally corresponds with Galil's chronology below with a difference of at most one year.<ref>[[Kenneth Kitchen]], How We Know When Solomon Ruled: Israel's Kings, BAR September/October 2001</ref>\n\n{| border=1 cellpadding=5 cellspacing=0\n|-\n!Albright/Thiele dates\n!Galil dates\n!Common/Biblical name\n!Regnal Name and style\n!width=20%|Notes\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n'''[[House of Saul]]'''\n|-  style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#ffffec;\"\n|''c.'' 1021\u20131000\n|''c.'' 1030\u20131010\n|'''[[Saul]]'''\n|[[Saul|'''Shaul''' ben Qish]], Melekh Ysra'el\n|Killed in battle, suicide\n|-  style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#ffffec;\"\n|''c.'' 1000\n|''c.'' 1010\u20131008\n|'''[[Ish-boseth|Ishbaal]]'''<br />('''[[Ish-boseth]]''')\n|[[Ish-boseth|'''Ishba'al''' ben Shaul]], Melekh Ysra'el\n|[[Assassination|Assassinated]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n'''[[Davidic line|House of David]]'''\n|-  style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#ffffec;\"\n|''c.'' 1000\u2013962\n|''c.'' 1008\u2013970\n|'''[[David]]'''\n|[[David|'''David''' ben Yishai]], Melekh Ysra\u2019el\n|Son-in-law of Saul, brother-in-law of Ish-boseth\n|-  style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#ffffec;\"\n|''c.'' 962\u2013''c.'' 922\n|''c.'' 970\u2013931\n|'''[[Solomon]]'''\n|[[Solomon|'''Sh'lomoh''' ben David]], Melekh Ysra\u2019el\n|Son of David and [[Bathsheba]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Biblical chronology]]\n* [[Historicity of the Bible]]\n* [[Ir Ovot]]\n* [[Kings of Israel and Judah]]\n* [[Kingdom of Israel (Samaria)]] (the northern kingdom after the split)\n* [[Kingdom of Judah]] (the southern kingdom after the split)\n* [[Israel]] (the modern country)\n* [[List of Jewish states and dynasties]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book\n|last1         = Davies\n|first1        = Philip\n|chapter       = Urban Religion and Rural Religion\n|editor1-last  = Stavrakopoulou\n|editor1-first = Francesca\n|editor2-last  = Barton\n|editor2-first = John\n|title         = Religious Diversity in Ancient Israel and Judah\n|publisher     = A&C Black\n|year          = 2010\n|chapter-url   = https://books.google.com/?id=kG_9-vki4ocC&printsec=frontcover\n|isbn          = \n|ref           = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n|last1     = Dever\n|first1    = William G.\n|title     = Beyond the Texts: An Archaeological Portrait of Ancient Israel and Judah\n|publisher = SBL Press\n|year      = 2017\n|url       = https://books.google.com/?id=mog6DwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover\n|isbn      = 9780884142171\n|ref       = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n|last1         = Hjelm\n|first1        = Ingrid\n|last2         = Thompson\n|first2        = Thomas L.\n|chapter       = Introduction\n|editor1-last  = Hjelm\n|editor1-first = Ingrid\n|editor2-last  = Thompson\n|editor2-first = Thomas L.\n|title         = History, Archaeology and The Bible Forty Years After \"Historicity\"\n|publisher     = Routledge\n|year          = 2016\n|chapter-url   = https://books.google.com/?id=PGOaCwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover\n|isbn          = \n|ref           = harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n|last1     = Moore\n|first1    = Megan Bishop\n|last2     = Kelle\n|first2    = Brad E.\n|title     = Biblical History and Israel's Past\n|publisher = Eerdmans\n|year      = 2011\n|url       = https://books.google.com/?id=Qjkz_8EMoaUC&pg=PA125\n|isbn      = 9780802862600\n|ref       = harv\n}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Israelites}}\n{{Ancient states and regions of the Levant |state=collapsed}}\n{{Portal bar|Asia|Israel|Palestine|Jordan|Judaism|Bible}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT: Kingdom Of Israel (United Monarchy)}}\n[[Category:10th-century BC disestablishments]]\n[[Category:11th-century BC establishments]]\n[[Category: Ancient Israel and Judah| ]]\n[[Category:David]]\n[[Category: Former countries in Western Asia]]\n[[Category: Former kingdoms|Israel, United Monarchy]]\n[[Category:Jewish polities|Israel]]\n[[Category: Political entities in the Land of Israel]]\n[[Category:Solomon]]\n[[Category: States and territories established in the 11th century BC]]\n[[Category: States and territories disestablished in the 10th century BC]]\n[[Category: Kingdom of Israel (united monarchy)| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the modern country|State of Israel|the two split kingdoms|Kingdom of Israel (Samaria)|and|Kingdom of Judah}}\n{{Infobox Former Country\n|native_name = \ud802\udd09\ud802\udd14\ud802\udd13\ud802\udd00\ud802\udd0b<ref>\n* {{cite book |last=Rollston |first=Chris A. |author-link=Christopher Rollston |title=Writing and Literacy in the World of Ancient Israel: Epigraphic Evidence from the Iron Age |year=2010 |publisher=Society of Biblical Literature |url=http://books.google.co.kr/books?id=kx9Uke_IfloC&pg=PA52 |pages=52\u201354 |isbn=978-1589831070 }}\n* {{cite book |last=Compston |first=Herbert F. B. |title=The Inscription on the Stele of M\u00e9\u0161a\u02bf |year=1919 |url=http://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Inscription_on_the_Stele_of_M%C3%A9%C5%A1a%CA%BF }}</ref>\n|conventional_long_name = Kingdom of Israel\n|common_name      = Kingdom of Israel\n|era              = [[Iron Age]]\n|government_type  = [[Hereditary monarchy|Hereditary]], [[Theocracy|theocratic]], and [[Absolute monarchy|absolute]] monarchy\n|common_languages = Hebrew, Aramaic\n|religion         = [[Yahwism]]<br>[[Polytheism]]<br>([[Canaanite Religion|Canaanite]] \u2022<br> [[Ancient Mesopotamian religion|Mesopotamian]] \u2022<br> [[Folk religion]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Ezekiel+8&version=NIV|title=Bible Gateway passage: Ezekiel 8 - New International Version|website=Bible Gateway}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://biblehub.com/1_kings/11-5.htm|title=1 Kings 11:5 Solomon followed Ashtoreth the goddess of the Sidonians and Molech the abomination of the Ammonites|website=biblehub.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://biblehub.com/2_kings/23-13.htm|title=2 Kings 23:13 The king also desecrated the high places east of Jerusalem, to the south of the Mount of Corruption, which King Solomon of Israel had built for Ashtoreth the abomination of the Sidonians, for Chemosh the abomination of the Moabites, and for Molech the abomination of the Ammonites|website=biblehub.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://biblehub.com/jeremiah/11-13.htm|title=Jeremiah 11:13 Your gods are indeed as numerous as your cities, O Judah, and the altars of shame you have set up--the altars to burn incense to Baal--are as many as the streets of Jerusalem|website=biblehub.com}}</ref><ref name=Finkelstein2001/>{{rp|240\u2013243}}\n|p1               = Tribes of Israel\n|flag_p1          = Menorah.svg\n|image_p1         = 12 Tribes of Israel Map.svg\n|image_map        = Kingdom of Israel 1020 map.svg\n|s1               = Kingdom of Israel (Samaria)\n|flag_s1          = Menorah.svg\n|s2               = Kingdom of Judah\n|flag_s2          = Menorah.svg\n|event_start      = [[Saul|Saul's ascension]]\n|year_start       = c. 1047 BCE\n|event_end        = [[Jeroboam's Revolt]]\n|year_end         = 930 BCE\n|capital          = [[Gibeah]] <small>(1030\u20131010 BCE)</small><br /> [[Mahanaim]] <small>(1010\u20131008)</small><br /> [[Hebron]] <small>(1008\u20131003)</small><br /> [[Jerusalem]] <small>(1003\u2013930)</small>\n|leader1          = [[Saul]]\n|leader2          = [[Ish-boseth|Ishbaal]]\n|leader3          = [[David]]\n|leader4          = [[Solomon]]\n|leader5          = [[Rehoboam]]\n|year_leader1     = 1047\u20131010 BCE\n|year_leader2     = 1010\u20131008\n|year_leader3     = 1008\u2013970\n|year_leader4     = 970\u2013931\n|year_leader5     = 931\u2013930\n|title_leader     = [[Kings of Israel and Judah|King]]\n|today            = \n{{flag|Egypt}}<br>{{flag|Israel}}<br>{{flag|Jordan}}<br>{{flag|Lebanon}}<br>{{flag|Palestine}}<br>{{flag|Syria}}\n}}\n\nThe '''United Monarchy''' ({{Lang-he-n|\u05d4\u05de\u05de\u05dc\u05db\u05d4 \u05d4\u05de\u05d0\u05d5\u05d7\u05d3\u05ea}}) is the name given to the [[Israelites|Israelite]]{{refn|group=note|name=israelite|This article uses the term \"Israelite\" as defined by ''The Encyclopedia of the Jewish Religion'': <blockquote>The name . . . signifies the people composed of &#91;[[Jacob]]'s&#93; descendants (the \"[[children of Israel]]\"), being applied (a) to the [[Twelve Tribes of Israel|whole people]] (including [[Tribe of Judah|Judah]]) . . . [but] (b) with the division of the kingdom after the death of [[Solomon]], to the [[Northern Kingdom]] only.\"<ref name=\"werblowskiwigoder1966\">{{cite book|chapter=Israelite|title=The Encyclopedia of the Jewish Religion|editor-last1=Werblowsky|editor-first1=R.J. Zwi|editor-link1=R.J. Zwi Werblowsky|editor-last2=Wigoder|editor-first2=Geoffrey|publisher=Holt, Rinehart and Winston|date=1966|pages=206\u2013207}}</ref></blockquote> }} kingdom of Israel and Judah,<ref name=\"cundall1972\">{{cite journal|author-last=Cundall|author-first=Arthur E. |title=The United Monarchy: fact or fiction?|journal= Vox Evangelica |volume=8 |year=1973|pages= 33\u201339|url=http://www.biblicalstudies.org.uk/pdf/vox/vol08/monarchy_cundall.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"harvey1996\">{{cite book|author-last=Harvey|author-first=Graham|date=1996|title=The True Israel: Uses of the Names Jew, Hebrew, and Israel in Ancient Jewish and Early Christian Literature|publisher=Brill Academic Publishers, Inc.|location=Boston|page=164|isbn=978-0-391-04119-6|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Dy5D90UapWsC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref><ref name=\"devaux1997\">{{cite book|last=de Vaux, O.P.|first=Roland|author-link=Roland de Vaux|translator-last=McHugh|translator-first=John|date=1997|title=Ancient Israel: Its Life and Institutions|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|location=Grand Rapids, Michigan|isbn=978-0-8028-4278-7|url=https://books.google.com/?id=A42yVk8kj8kC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> during the reigns of [[Saul]], [[David]] and [[Solomon]], as depicted in the [[Hebrew Bible]]. This is traditionally dated between 1050 BCE and 930 BCE. On the succession of Solomon's son, [[Rehoboam]], around 930 BCE, the biblical account reports that the country split into two kingdoms: the [[Kingdom of Israel (Samaria)|Kingdom of Israel]] (including the cities of [[Shechem]] and [[Samaria (ancient city)|Samaria]]) in the north and the [[Kingdom of Judah]] (containing Jerusalem) in the south.\n\nIn contemporary scholarship the united monarchy is generally held to be a literary construction and not a historical reality, pointing to the lack of archaeological evidence. It is generally accepted that a \"[[Davidic line|House of David]]\" existed, but many believe that David could have only been the monarch or [[chieftain]] of Judah, which was likely small, and that the northern kingdom was a separate development. There are some dissenters to this view.<ref name=\"lipschits\">{{cite book|last1=Lipschits|first1=Oded|editor1-last=Berlin|editor1-first=Adele|editor2-last=Brettler|editor2-first=Marc Zvi|title=The Jewish Study Bible|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-997846-5|year=2014|edition=2nd|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yErYBAAAQBAJ&dq|language=en|chapter=The history of Israel in the biblical period}}</ref><ref name=\"Finkelstein2001\">{{cite book|last1=Finkelstein|first1=Israel|author-link1=Israel Finkelstein|last2=Silberman|first2=Neil Asher|author-link2=Neil Asher Silberman|title=The Bible Unearthed: Archaeology's New Vision of Ancient Israel and the Origin of its Stories|date=2001|publisher=Simon & Schuster|location=New York|isbn=978-0-684-86912-4|url=https://books.google.com/?id=lu6ywyJr0CMC&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Bible+Unearthed:+Archaeology%27s+New+Vision+of+Ancient+Israel+and+the+Origin+of+its+Stories#v=onepage&q=The%20Bible%20Unearthed%3A%20Archaeology's%20New%20Vision%20of%20Ancient%20Israel%20and%20the%20Origin%20of%20its%20Stories&f=false}}</ref><ref name=Kuhrtp438>{{cite book|last=Kuhrt|first=Am\u00e9lie|author-link=Am\u00e9lie Kuhrt|title=The Ancient Near East, c. 3000-330 BC, Band 1|year=1995|publisher=Routledge|location=New York|isbn=978-0-41516-762-8|page=438|url=https://books.google.com/?id=V_sfMzRPTgoC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Kuhrt,+Amiele+(1995).+The+Ancient+Near+East.#v=onepage&q=Kuhrt%2C%20Amiele%20(1995).%20The%20Ancient%20Near%20East.&f=false}}</ref><ref name=\"bibleinterp.com\">{{cite web|last1=Wright|first1=Jacob L.|author-link=Jacob L. Wright|title=David, King of Judah (not Israel)|url=http://www.bibleinterp.com/articles/2014/07/wri388001.shtml|website=The Bible and Interpretation|date=July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n{{Main|Books of Samuel|History of Ancient Israel and Judah}}\nAccording to standard [[Source criticism (biblical studies)|source criticism]], a number of distinct source texts were spliced together to produce the current Books of Samuel.<ref name=\"bibleinterp.com\"/> The most prominent in the early parts of the first book are the pro-monarchical source and the anti-monarchical source. In identifying these two sources, two separate accounts can be reconstructed. The anti-monarchical source describes [[Samuel (Bible)|Samuel]] as having thoroughly routed the [[Philistines]], yet begrudgingly accepting the people's demand for a ruler, subsequently appointing Saul by [[cleromancy]].{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\nThe pro-monarchical source describes the divinely appointed birth of [[Saul]] (a single word being changed by a later editor so that it referred to Samuel instead), and his leading of an army to victory over the [[Ammon (nation)|Ammonites]], resulted in the clamouring of the people for him to lead them against the Philistines, whereupon he is appointed king.<ref name=\"jones2001\">{{Cite book|last=Jones|first=Gwilym H.|chapter=1 and 2 Samuel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wCRYl9Ikk6EC&pg=PA196|editor-last1=Barton|editor-first1=John|editor-link1=John Barton (theologian)|editor-last2=Muddiman|editor-first2=John|editor-link2=John Muddiman|title=The Oxford Bible Commentary|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2001|pages= 197\u2013199|isbn=978-0-19875-500-5}}</ref>\n\n[[Textual critic]]s also point to disparities in the account of David's rise to power as indicative of separate threads being merged later to create a [[Golden Age]] of a united monarchy. David is thought by scholars to have been a ruler in Judah, while Israel, comparatively immense and highly developed, continued unfettered. [[Modern archaeology]] also supports this view.<ref name=Finkelstein2001/>\n\nMost scholars believe the Books of Samuel exhibit too many [[anachronism]]s to have been a contemporary account. For example, there is mention of later [[armor]] (1 Samuel 17:4\u20137, 38\u201339; 25:13), use of [[camel]]s (1 Samuel 30:17), [[cavalry]] (as distinct from [[chariotry]]) (1 Samuel 13:5, 2 Samuel 1:6), and iron picks and axes (as though they were common) (2 Samuel 12:31). The historicity of the conquest described in the Book of Samuel is not attested, and many scholars regard this conquest as legendary in origin, particularly given the lack of evidence for the battles described involving the destruction of the Canaanite peoples. Most scholars believe that Samuel was compiled in the 8th century BCE (rather than the 10th century when most of the events described take place) based on both historical and legendary sources, primarily serving to fill the gap in Israelite history after the events described in [[Deuteronomy]]. This gap in the historical record is characteristic of the [[Late Bronze Age collapse]];<ref name=\"AruzSeymour2016\">{{cite book|editor-first1=Joan|editor-last1=Aruz|editor-first2=Michael|editor-last2=Seymour|first=Ann E.|last=Killebrew|title=Assyria to Iberia: Art and Culture in the Iron Age|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WBrfDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA38|date=30 December 2016|publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art|isbn=978-1-58839-606-8|pages=30\u201338}}</ref> cultural memories of times before the disaster often became embellished as stories of a \"lost golden age\", as in the Trojan [[Epic Cycle]].<ref name=\"Kalimi2018\">Cf. {{cite book|first=Isaac|last=Kalimi|title=Writing and Rewriting the Story of Solomon in Ancient Israel|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L9Z7DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA47|date=29 November 2018|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-108-58837-9|pages=47\u201348}}</ref>\n\n==Archaeological record==\n\nAccording to [[Israel Finkelstein]] and [[Neil Asher Silberman|Neil Silberman]], authors of ''[[The Bible Unearthed]]'', ideas of a united monarchy are not accurate history but rather \"creative expressions of a powerful religious reform movement,\" possibly \"based on certain historical kernels.\"<ref name=Finkelstein2001/> Finkelstein and Silberman do accept that David and Solomon were real kings of Judah about the 10th century BCE, but they cite the fact that the earliest independent reference to the Kingdom of Israel dates to about 890 BCE, while that for the kingdom of Judah dates to about 750 BCE.<ref name=\"finkelsteinsilberman2007\">{{cite book |last1=Finkelstein |first1=Israel |last2=Silberman |first2=Neil Asher |title=David and Solomon: In Search of the Bible's Sacred Kings and the Roots of the Western Tradition |date=2007 |publisher=Simon and Schuster |location=New York |isbn=978-1-416-55688-6 |page=20 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/David_and_Solomon.html?id=uH7Kg9yEc7AC}}</ref> This is supported by Jonathan Tubb, who argues that the story of the united monarchy was fabricated as a Golden Age tale during the [[Babylonian captivity|Exile]]. He accepts the historicity of David and Solomon but cautions that \"[t]hey must be seen . . . as local [[folk hero]]es and not as rulers of international status.\"<ref name=Tubbp115>{{cite book|last=Tubb|first=Jonathan|title=Canaanites|year=2006|publisher=The British Museum Press|location=London|isbn=978-0-7141-2766-8|page=115}}</ref> [[Oded Lipschits]] wrote in the ''Jewish Study Bible'' that \"the premonarchic period long ago became a literary description of the mythological roots, the early beginnings of the nation and the way to describe the right of Israel on its land. The archeological evidence also does not support the existence of a united monarchy under David and Solomon as described in the Bible, so the rubric of \"united monarchy\" is best abandoned, although it remains useful for discussing how the Bible views the Israelite past\".<ref name=\"lipschits\"/>\n\nOn the other hand, while [[Am\u00e9lie Kuhrt]] does acknowledge that \"there are no royal inscriptions from the time of the united monarchy (indeed very little written material altogether), and not a single contemporary reference to either David or Solomon,\" she concludes that \"[a]gainst this must be set the evidence for substantial development and growth at several sites, which is plausibly related to the tenth century.\"<ref name=Kuhrtp438 /> [[Kenneth Kitchen]] reaches a similar conclusion, arguing that \"the physical archaeology of tenth-century [[Canaan]] is consistent with the former existence of a unified state on its terrain.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Kitchen|first=Kenneth|title=On the Reliability of the Old Testament|year=2003|publisher=William B. Eerdmans Publishing Company|location=Grand Rapids, Michigan|isbn=978-0-80280-396-2|page=158|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Kw6U05qBiXcC&lpg=PA158&dq=%22the%20physical%20archaeology%20of%20tenth-century%20Canaan%20is%20consistent%20with%20the%20former%20existence%20of%20a%20unified%20state%20on%20its%20terrain%22&pg=PA158#v=onepage&q=%22the%20physical%20archaeology%20of%20tenth-century%20Canaan%20is%20consistent%20with%20the%20former%20existence%20of%20a%20unified%20state%20on%20its%20terrain%22&f=false}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Qeiyafa city wall1.jpg|right|thumb|Aerial view of [[Khirbet Qeiyafa]].]]\nExcavations at [[Khirbet Qeiyafa]], an [[Iron Age]] site located in Judah, found an urbanized settlement [[radiocarbon dated]] well before scholars such as Finklestein suggest [[urbanization]] began in Judah, supporting existence of a Judahite kingdom. The [[Israel Antiquities Authority]] stated: \"The excavations at Khirbat Qeiyafa clearly reveal an urban society that existed in Judah already in the late eleventh century BCE. It can no longer be argued that the Kingdom of Judah developed only in the late eighth century BCE or at some other later date.\"<ref name=\"garfinkel2012\">{{cite web |last1=Garfinkel |first1=Yossi |last2=Ganor |first2=Sa'ar |last3=Hasel |first3=Michael |title=Journal 124: Khirbat Qeiyafa preliminary report |url=http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=1989 |website=Hadashot Arkheologiyot: Excavations and Surveys in Israel |publisher=Israel Antiquities Authority |accessdate=12 June 2018 |ref=garfinkel2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120623021750/http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.aspx?id=1989 |archivedate=1 January 2018 |date=19 April 2012}}</ref> The techniques and interpretations used to reach some conclusions related to Khirbet Qeiyafa have been criticized by some scholars, among them Finkelstein and Alexander Fantalkin of [[Tel Aviv University]].<ref name=\"finkelsteinfantalkin2012\">{{cite journal |last1=Finkelstein |first1=Israel |last2=Fantalkin |first2=Alexander |title=Khirbet Qeiyafa: an unsensational archaeological and historical interpretation |journal=Tel Aviv |date=May 2012 |volume=39 |pages=38\u201363 |doi=10.1179/033443512x13226621280507 |url=http://archaeology.tau.ac.il/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/Qeiyafa_Unsensational_Interpretation.pdf |accessdate=12 June 2018 |ref=finkelsteinfantalkin2012}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, Israeli archaeologists discovered massive [[fortification]]s in the ruins of the ancient city of [[Gath (city)|Gath]], supposed birthplace of [[Goliath]]. The size of the fortifications show Gath to have been a very large city in the 10th century BCE, perhaps the largest in Canaan at the time. The professor leading the dig, [[Aren Maeir]], estimated that Gath was as much as four times the size of contemporary Jerusalem, casting doubt that David's kingdom could have been as powerful as described in the Bible.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.haaretz.com/beta/.premium-1.669425|title=Philistine city of Gath a lot more powerful than thought, archaeologists suggest|last1=Hasson|first1=Nir |work=Haaretz|publisher=Haaretz Daily Newspaper Ltd.|date=4 August 2015|accessdate=12 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Finkelstein claimed that mounting evidence from archaeological digs has led him to believe that a united monarchy of sorts did exist, but that it was under [[Jeroboam II]], some two centuries after the reigns of David and Solomon. Finkelstein claimed that the Biblical narrative was likely invented under the reign of King [[Josiah]] to justify expansion and that the historical united monarchy was the inspiration.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/archaeology/.premium.MAGAZINE-meet-the-real-king-david-the-one-the-bible-didn-t-want-you-to-know-about-1.7062754|title=Meet the Real King David, the One the Bible Didn\u2019t Want You to Know About|last=David|first=Ariel|date=2019-03-27|work=Haaretz|access-date=2019-04-24|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Biblical narrative==\n===Origin===\n{{History of Israel}}\nAccording to the [[Book of Judges]], before the rise of the united monarchy the [[Israelite]] tribes lived as a [[Confederated Tribes of Israel|confederation]] under ''[[ad hoc]]'' [[charisma]]tic leaders called [[Biblical judges|judges]]. [[Abimelech (Judges)|Abimelech]] the first judge to be declared king by the men of [[Shechem]] and the house of Millo (Bet Millo), reigned over Israel for three years before he was killed during the Battle of [[Tubas|Thebez]].\n\nAccording to the biblical account, the united monarchy was formed when there was a large popular expression in favour of introducing a king to rule over the decentralised Israelite confederacy. Increasing pressure from the [[Philistines]] and other neighboring peoples is said by the Bible to have forced the Israelites to unite as state following the [[anointing]] of Saul by Samuel. The Bible treats the notion of kingship as having been [[anathema]], it being viewed as the placing of one man in a position of reverence and power that ought to be reserved for [[God]].<ref>{{cite web |title=1 Samuel 8.6 |url=https://www.sefaria.org/I_Samuel.8.7?lang=en |website=Sefaria |accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Civil war===\nDavid and Saul become bitter enemies, at least from Saul's point of view, although sources describe [[Jonathan (1 Samuel)|Jonathan]], Saul's son, and [[Michal]], Saul's daughter, as assisting David to escape Saul, ultimately leading to a brief reconciliation before Saul's death.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\nAccording to the [[Second Book of Samuel]], Saul's disobedience prompts God to curtail his reign and hand his kingdom over to another dynasty. Saul dies in battle against the Philistines{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} after a reign of just two years.<ref>Lemaire, Andre. [http://www.myjewishlearning.com/history/Ancient_and_Medieval_History/2500_BCE-539_BCE/Social_History/Sauls_United_Kingdom.shtml?p=2 \"King Saul.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527220959/http://www.myjewishlearning.com/history/Ancient_and_Medieval_History/2500_BCE-539_BCE/Social_History/Sauls_United_Kingdom.shtml?p=2 |date=2014-05-27 }} ''My Jewish Learning''.  27 May 2014.</ref> His heir, [[Ish-bosheth|Ishbaal]], rules for only two years before being [[assassination|assassinated]]. David, heretofore king of Judah only, ends the conspiracy and is appointed king of Israel in Ishbaal's place. Some textual critics and biblical scholars suggest that David was actually responsible for the assassination and that David's innocence was a later invention to legitimize his actions.<ref>{{cite book|author=Stanley Jerome Isser|title=The Sword of Goliath: David in Heroic Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OHT6Y-6RCewC&pg=PA152|date=January 2003|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-12737-1|pages=152\u2013}}</ref>\n\nIsrael [[insurrection|rebels]] against David and appoints David's son [[Absalom]] king, forcing David into [[exile]] east of the [[Jordan River|Jordan]].{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} David eventually launches a successful counterattack that results in the loss of Absalom. Having retaken Judah and asserted control over Israel, David returns west of the Jordan. Throughout the remainder of his reign, he continues to suppress rebellions that arise among the people of Israel.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\nThis section of the biblical text, and the bulk of the remainder of the Books of Samuel, is thought by textual critics to belong to a single large source known as the [[Court History of David]]. Although reflecting the [[polemic|political bias]] of the kingdom of Judah following the [[Kingdom of Israel (Samaria)#Destruction of the kingdom|destruction of Israel]], the source remains somewhat more neutral than the pro- and antimonarchical sources comprising earlier parts of the text. Israel and Judah are portrayed in this source as quite distinct kingdoms.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n===Golden Age===\nPrior to the ascension of Saul, the city of [[Shiloh (Biblical)|Shiloh]] is seen as the [[national capital]], at least in the religious sense, a claim that from an archaeological standpoint is considered plausible. Throughout the monarchy of Saul, the capital is located in [[Gibeah]]. After Saul's death, Ishbaal rules over the kingdom of Israel from [[Mahanaim]], while David establishes the capital of the kingdom of Judah in [[Hebron]].{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n \nFollowing the [[civil war]] with Saul, David forges a strong and unified Israelite monarchy, reigning c. 1000 to 961 BCE<ref name=\"Judges Chronology\">{{cite book|last=Edited by Robert G. Boling|title=Judges (The Anchor Yale Bible Commentaries)|year=1975|publisher=Doubleday|location=Garden City, New York|isbn=978-0300139457|page=XXI}}</ref> and establishing [[Jerusalem]] as his national capital in 1006 BCE.<ref name=\"aice2018\">{{cite web |title=The Jewish temples: Jerusalem in the First Temple Period (1006\u2013586 BCE) |url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jerusalem-in-the-first-temple-period |website=Jewish Virtual Library |publisher=American-Israeli Cooperative Enterprise |accessdate=14 June 2018 |ref=aice2018}}</ref> Some modern archaeologists, however, believe that the two distinct cultures and geographic entities of Judah and Israel continued uninterrupted, and that if a political union between them did exist, it possibly had no practical effect on their relationship.<ref name=Finkelstein2001/>\n\nIn the biblical account, David embarks on successful military campaigns against the enemies of Judah and Israel, defeating such regional entities as the [[Philistines]] to secure his borders. Israel grows from kingdom to empire, its sphere of influence\u2014militarily and politically\u2014expanding to control the weaker [[client state]]s of [[Philistia]], [[Moab]], [[Edom]] and [[Ammon]], with Aramaean [[city-state]]s [[Zobah|Aram-Zobah]] and [[Aram-Damascus]] becoming [[vassal state]]s.<ref>{{Bibleverse|2 Sam|8:1-14|NRSV}}</ref> The imperial border is described as stretching from the [[Mediterranean Sea]] to the [[Arabian Desert]], from the [[Red Sea]] to the [[Euphrates River]]. Some modern archaeologists believe that the area under the control of Judah and Israel, excluding the [[Phoenicia]]n territories on the shore of the [[Mediterranean]], did not exceed 34,000 square kilometres (13,000 sq mi), of which the kingdom of Israel encompassed about {{convert|24000|km2}}.{{citation needed|date=February 2014}}\n\nDavid is succeeded by his son [[Solomon]], who obtains the throne in a somewhat disreputable manner from rival claimant [[Adonijah]], his elder brother.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} The reign of Solomon (c. 961 to 922 BCE)<ref name=\"Judges Chronology\" /> proves to be a period of unprecedented peace, prosperity, and cultural development. Solomon embarks on an aggressive campaign of public building, erecting the [[Solomon's Temple|First Temple]] in Jerusalem with assistance from the [[King Hiram I|King of Tyre]], with whom he has maintained the strong alliance forged by his father.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} Like the [[David's Palace|palace of David]], Solomon's temple is designed and built with the assistance of Tyrian architects, master craftsmen, skilled labourers, money, jewels, cedar, and other goods obtained in exchange for land ceded to [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]].{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\nSolomon goes on to rebuild numerous major cities, including [[Tel Megiddo|Megiddo]], [[Tel Hazor|Hazor]], and [[Gezer]]. Some scholars have attributed aspects of archaeological remains excavated from this sites, including six-chambered gates and [[ashlar]] palaces, to this building programme. However, excavation teams at Megiddo later established that these structures are from different time periods. [[Yigael Yadin]] subsequently concluded that the stables once believed to have served Solomon's vast collection of horses were actually built by [[King Ahab]] in the 9th century BCE.<ref name=\"finkelsteinmaza2007\">{{cite book|last1=Finkelstein|first1=Israel|last2=Maza|first2=Amihay|date=2007|title=The Quest for the Historical Israel|location=Atlanta|publisher=Society of Biblical Literature|isbn=978-1-58983-277-0|page=102|url=https://books.google.com/?id=jpbngoKHg8gC&q=102#v=snippet&q=102&f=false}}</ref>\n\n===End===\n{{Main|Jeroboam's Revolt|Kingdom of Israel (Samaria)|Kingdom of Judah}}\n[[File:Kingdoms of Israel and Judah map 830.svg|thumb|Map showing the Kingdoms of Israel (blue) and Judah (orange), ancient Southern Levant borders and ancient cities such as Urmomium and Jerash. The map shows the region in the 9th century BCE.]]\nFollowing Solomon's death in c. 926 BCE, tensions between the northern part of Israel containing the ten northern tribes, and the southern section dominated by Jerusalem and the southern tribes reached boiling point. When Solomon's successor [[Rehoboam]] dealt tactlessly with economic complaints of the northern tribes, in about 930 BCE (there are differences of opinion as to the actual year) the United Kingdom of Israel and Judah split into two kingdoms: the northern [[Kingdom of Israel (Samaria)|Kingdom of Israel]], which included the cities of [[Shechem]] and [[Samaria]], and the southern [[Kingdom of Judah]], which contained Jerusalem, with most of the non-Israelite provinces achieving independence.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nThe Kingdom of Israel (or Northern Kingdom, or Samaria) existed as an independent state until 722 BCE when it was conquered by the [[Assyrian Empire]], while the Kingdom of Judah (or Southern Kingdom) existed as an independent state until 586 BCE when it was conquered by the [[Neo-Babylonian Empire]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}\n\n==Biblical chronology==\n{{Further|Kings of Israel and Judah}}\nMany alternative chronologies have been suggested, and there is no ultimate consensus between the different factions and scholarly disciplines concerned with this period, as to when it is depicted as having begun or when it ended.<ref>{{cite book|last=Shanks|first=Hershel|title=Ancient Israel (3rd Edition)|year=2010|publisher=Pearson|isbn=978-0205096435}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Friedman|first=Richard|title=Who Wrote The Bible|year=1987|publisher=HarperOne|isbn=978-0060630355|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/whowrotebible000frie}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Bloom|first=Harold|title=The Book of J|year=2004|publisher=Grove Press|isbn=978-0802141910}}</ref>\n\nMost bibical scholars follow either of the older chronologies established by [[William F. Albright]] or [[Edwin R. Thiele]], or the newer chronology of [[Gershon Galil]], all of which are shown below. All dates are BCE. Thiele's chronology generally corresponds with Galil's chronology below with a difference of at most one year.<ref>[[Kenneth Kitchen]], How We Know When Solomon Ruled: Israel's Kings, BAR September/October 2001</ref>\n\n{| border=1 cellpadding=5 cellspacing=0\n|-\n!Albright/Thiele dates\n!Galil dates\n!Common/Biblical name\n!Regnal Name and style\n!width=20%|Notes\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n'''[[House of Saul]]'''\n|-  style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#ffffec;\"\n|''c.'' 1021\u20131000\n|''c.'' 1030\u20131010\n|'''[[Saul]]'''\n|[[Saul|'''Shaul''' ben Qish]], Melekh Ysra'el\n|Killed in battle, suicide\n|-  style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#ffffec;\"\n|''c.'' 1000\n|''c.'' 1010\u20131008\n|'''[[Ish-boseth|Ishbaal]]'''<br />('''[[Ish-boseth]]''')\n|[[Ish-boseth|'''Ishba'al''' ben Shaul]], Melekh Ysra'el\n|[[Assassination|Assassinated]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n'''[[Davidic line|House of David]]'''\n|-  style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#ffffec;\"\n|''c.'' 1000\u2013962\n|''c.'' 1008\u2013970\n|'''[[David]]'''\n|[[David|'''David''' ben Yishai]], Melekh Ysra\u2019el\n|Son-in-law of Saul, brother-in-law of Ish-boseth\n|-  style=\"vertical-align:top; background:#ffffec;\"\n|''c.'' 962\u2013''c.'' 922\n|''c.'' 970\u2013931\n|'''[[Solomon]]'''\n|[[Solomon|'''Sh'lomoh''' ben David]], Melekh Ysra\u2019el\n|Son of David and [[Bathsheba]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Biblical chronology]]\n* [[Historicity of the Bible]]\n* [[Ir Ovot]]\n* [[Kings of Israel and Judah]]\n* [[Kingdom of Israel (Samaria)]] (the northern kingdom after the split)\n* [[Kingdom of Judah]] (the southern kingdom after the split)\n* [[Israel]] (the modern country)\n* [[List of Jewish states and dynasties]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book\n|last1         = Davies\n|first1        = Philip\n|chapter       = Urban Religion and Rural Religion\n|editor1-last  = Stavrakopoulou\n|editor1-first = Francesca\n|editor2-last  = Barton\n|edit